5":"1285","1351":"1351","April 1317":"April 1317","1290":"1290","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1377":"1377","1321":"1321","1277":"1277","1299":"1299","1298":"1298","about 1298":"about 1298","1317":"1317","Greystoke, Cumberland, England":"Greystoke, Cumberland, England","Grimethorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Grimethorpe, Yorkshire, England","Hilton, Yorkshire, England":"Hilton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Greystoke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Graystock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graystock","meanings":["English: locative name, from Greystoke (Cumb), recorded as  <i>Graystock</i> in 1291."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Greystoke was born in 1300, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert FitzRalph, was 24 and her mother, Elizabeth Neville, was 14. She had at least 1 son with Robert Hilton. She died in 1321, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1300–1321":"1300–1321","1298–1358":"1298–1358","1299–1323":"1299–1323","1290–1351":"1290–1351","1321–1377":"1321–1377","1277–1317":"1277–1317","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1285":"1285","1351":"1351","April 1317":"aprill 1317","1290":"1290","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1377":"1377","1321":"1321","1277":"1277","1299":"1299","1298":"1298","about 1298":"umbes 1298","1317":"1317","Greystoke, Cumberland, England":"Greystoke, Cumberland, England","Grimethorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Grimethorpe, Yorkshire, England","Hilton, Yorkshire, England":"Hilton, 